# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We Use DSU for this Problem. Pretty Much the Basic implementation without any complications. Just whenver two characters are to be set equivalent , set the parent of bigger parent of the characters to the smaller parent of the character. 
See the code for more clarity.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(logn)

- Space complexity: O(n)


# Code
```
class DSU
{
public:
	int parent[26];
	DSU()
	{
		for (int i = 0; i < 26; ++i)
		{
			parent[i] = i; // setting the parent of 'a' to 'a'
		}
	}

	int find(int n)
	{
		if (parent[n] == n)
		{
			return n;
		}

		return parent[n] = find(parent[n]);
	}

	void unite(int x, int y)
	{

        int par_x = find(x);
        int par_y = find(y);

        if(par_x == par_y){
            return;
        }

		if (par_x < par_y)
		{
			parent[par_y] = par_x;

		}else{
            parent[par_x] = par_y;
	    }
    }

};
class Solution {
public:

    string smallestEquivalentString(string s1, string s2, string baseStr) {

        int n = s1.size();
        DSU wed = DSU(); 
        for(int i=0;i<n;++i)
        {
            wed.unite(s1[i]-'a',s2[i]-'a');

        }
        string res = "";

        for(char p:baseStr)
        {
            res += char (wed.find(p-'a') + 'a');
        }

        return res;

    }
};
```

