# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Maintain a map of all lowercase characters where each character points to the smallest equivalent character at any given time. Update this map as we discover equivalences between the characters of strings `s1` and `s2`, one character at a time. Finally use this map to convert the `baseStr` to the smallest equivalent string.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Create a map of all lowercase characters and initialize them to point to their own value.
2. Iterate over each character of strings `s1` and `s2`.
3. Look up the map for the smallest equivalent characters for both the characters of `s1` and `s2`.
4. Replace all instances of the larger equivalent character with the smaller one all throughout the map.
5. Now use the final state of the map to convert the `baseStr` one character at a time to the smallest equivalent string.

# Complexity
- N is the length of strings `s1` and `s2`
- M is the length of string `baseStr`

- Time complexity: $$O(N + M)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
  public String smallestEquivalentString(String s1, String s2, String baseStr) {
    var map = new char[26];

    for (var i=0; i<26; i++)
      map[i] = (char) ('a' + i);

    for (var i=0; i < s1.length(); i++) {
      var a = map[s1.charAt(i) - 'a'];
      var b = map[s2.charAt(i) - 'a'];

      if (a == b) continue;

      var a1 = a < b ? a : b;
      var b1 = a < b ? b : a;

      for (var j=0; j<26; j++)
        if (map[j] == b1)
          map[j] = a1;
    }
    var sb = new StringBuilder();

    for (var i=0; i < baseStr.length(); i++)
      sb.append(map[baseStr.charAt(i) - 'a']);

    return sb.toString();
  }
}
