# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We can think of this problem as a problem of finding disjoint sets of characters. Characters that are equivalent form connected components, and we want to find the smallest character within each connected component to represent the entire component.
We'll use a disjoint set data structure to efficiently manage the connected components. The DisjointSet class will help us keep track of which characters are equivalent and which character is the representative (smallest) character for each connected component.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
**Disjoint Set Setup:**

Create a DisjointSet instance with a size of 26 (assuming lowercase English alphabets). This set will represent the connected components of equivalent characters.
Initialize each character as its own parent in the disjoint set, and set the size of each component to 1.
Process Equivalent Pairs:

Iterate through each character index i from 0 to the length of s1 (or s2), where s1[i] and s2[i] represent equivalent characters.
For each pair (s1[i], s2[i]), call the unionBySmallerSize method of the DisjointSet to merge the components of characters s1[i] - 'a' and s2[i] - 'a'.
This operation ensures that characters in the same connected component will have the same representative character, which is the smallest character in that component.

**Building Equivalent String:**

Now that we've established the relationships between equivalent characters using the disjoint set, we can construct the smallest equivalent string for baseStr.
Iterate through each character c in baseStr.
Find the representative character of the connected component that c belongs to using the findUPar method of the disjoint set.
Append the representative character to the final answer string.
Output:

The final answer string contains the smallest equivalent string for the given baseStr based on the equivalent character pairs from s1 and s2.
Return the answer string as the result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(n+m)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(1)

# Code
```
class DisjointSet {
    public:
        vector<int> parent,size;

        DisjointSet(int n) {
            parent.resize(n);
            size.resize(n);

            for(int i=0;i<n;i++) {
                parent[i] = i;
                size[i] = 1;
            }
        }

        int findUPar(int node) {
            if(parent[node] == node)
                return node;

            return parent[node] = findUPar(parent[node]);
        }


        void unionBySmallerSize(int u,int v) {
            int ultU = findUPar(u);
            int ultV = findUPar(v);

            if(ultU == ultV)
                return;

            if(ultU < ultV) {
                parent[ultV] = ultU;
            }
            else {
                parent[ultU] = ultV;
            }
        }
};

class Solution {
public:
    string smallestEquivalentString(string s1, string s2, string baseStr) {
        DisjointSet ds(26);

        int n = s1.length();

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++) {
            int char1 = s1[i] - 'a';
            int char2 = s2[i] - 'a';

            ds.unionBySmallerSize(char1,char2);
        }


        string ans;

        for(char it : baseStr) {
            int tempInd = ds.findUPar(it-'a');

            char temp = (char)(tempInd + 'a');

            ans += temp;
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
