# Intuition
1. We cannot use HashMap or Array of Arraylist because the transitive property wouldn't work
2. We have to use some kind of data structure that would give us the lexicographically smallest character after keeping the transitive property in mind
3. So, Union-Find is the only way where we can get the lexicographically smallest character every time when we make the lexicographically smallest character as the parent of the character of each group

# Approach
1. We have to create groups - Here, we create unionise the characters 
2. We have to get the lexicographically smallest character so, we make this the parent of each group
3. Lastly, get the smallest character by using the find function.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(s1.length())

- Space complexity: O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    int find(int parent[], int i) {
        if (parent[i] == i)
            return i;
        return parent[i] = find(parent, parent[i]); 
    }

    void Union(int parent[], int x, int y) {
        if(y < x) parent[x] = y;
        else parent[y] = x;
    }

    public String smallestEquivalentString(String s1, String s2, String baseStr) {
        int[] parent = new int[26];

        for (int i = 0; i < 26; ++i)
            parent[i] = i;

        for(int i=0; i<s1.length(); i++) {
            int x = find(parent, s1.charAt(i)-'a');
            int y = find(parent, s2.charAt(i)-'a');
            Union(parent, x, y);
        } 

        StringBuilder ans = new StringBuilder();
        for(int i=0; i<baseStr.length(); i++) {
            ans.append((char)(find(parent, baseStr.charAt(i)-'a')+'a'));
        }

        return ans.toString();
    }
}
```

