solutions.content:
The key point of this DFS is that we need to remember from which cell we have come to this cell to `avoid back and forth`.

Space: O(m*n) such that m=grid.length, n= grid[0].length.
Time: O(m*n): because every time we start DFS, one cell is marked as visited at least.

```
class Solution {
  public boolean containsCycle(char[][] grid) {
    int m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
    boolean[][] isVisited = new boolean[m][n];
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
      for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
        if (!isVisited[i][j]) {
          if (hasCycle(grid, 0, i, j, grid[i][j], isVisited)) return true; // 0 is dummy direction of move.
        }
      }
    }
    return false;
  }

  // @param dir: direction of move. dummy:0, down:1,left:2,up:3,right:4 for each.
  private boolean hasCycle(char[][] grid, int dir, int i, int j, char c, boolean[][] isVisited) {
    if (i < 0 || grid.length <= i || j < 0 || grid[0].length <= j || grid[i][j] != c) return false;
    if (isVisited[i][j]) return true;
    isVisited[i][j] = true;
    return (dir != 3 && hasCycle(grid, 1, i + 1, j, c, isVisited)) // move `down` if previous move was not `up`.
        || (dir != 1 && hasCycle(grid, 3, i - 1, j, c, isVisited)) // move `up` if previous move was not `down`.
        || (dir != 2 && hasCycle(grid, 4, i, j + 1, c, isVisited)) // move `right` if previous move was not `left`.
        || (dir != 4 && hasCycle(grid, 2, i, j - 1, c, isVisited)); // move `left` if previous move was not `right`.
  }
}
```

