This java soultion is easy to undestand and follows standard DFS algo, It is also easy to explain in interviews to the panel.
TC - O(N  * M) 
SC - O(N  * M)
where,
N - graph.length, M = graph[0].length;

**Math.abs(dist[x][y] - dist[r][c]) >= 3)** This checks if length of cycle is greater than or equal to 4.
***why then >=3*** in my code 

 *Because,  I have passed starting path length as 1 and I am incrementing 1 each time and hence when it's reaches the block which is adjacent to starting block the minimum dist value will be 4 in it, so the diff will be >=3.*

```

class Solution {
    int[][] dir = { {0,-1}, {-1,0}, {0,1}, {1,0} };

    public boolean containsCycle(char[][] grid) {
        int n = grid.length, m = grid[0].length;
        int[][] dist = new int[n][m];

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<m;j++){
                if(dist[i][j]==0){
                    if(dfs(1,i, j, n, m, grid, dist)){
                        return true;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }

    private boolean dfs(int path, int r, int c,int n, int m, char[][] graph, int[][] dist){
        dist[r][c] = path;
        for(int d=0;d<4;d++){
            int x = r + dir[d][0];
            int y = c + dir[d][1];
            if(x>=0 && x<n && y>=0 && y<m && graph[r][c] == graph[x][y]){
                if(dist[x][y]==0){
                    if(dfs(path + 1, x, y, n, m, graph, dist)) return true;
                } else if(Math.abs(dist[x][y] - dist[r][c]) >= 3){
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}

